---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { APPS, SEGMENTS, USE_CASES, allPaths, appBySlug, appPairs, description, pageTitle, siteFromHost } from '../content';
const site = siteFromHost();
const slug = Astro.params.slug || '';
const path = Array.isArray(slug) ? slug.join('/') : slug;
const parts = path.split('/').filter(Boolean);
const title = pageTitle(site, path);
const desc = description(site, path);
function channelApps(){ return APPS.filter(a => a.channels.includes(site.channel) || a.channels.includes('marketing')); }
let valid = allPaths().includes(path);
if (!valid) return Astro.redirect('/');
const pairs = appPairs();
const primaryApps = channelApps().slice(0,12);
const operatingNotes = "A Shopify marketing app should be judged by the operating load it creates after the first launch. The attractive demo is not enough. Merchants need clean customer data, useful product context, safe consent handling, clear reporting, and a workflow a small team can repeat every week. The right decision usually comes from mapping the next ninety days: which flow must ship, which segments matter, which offers protect margin, who owns creative, and how revenue quality will be measured after the campaign is live.";
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={desc} site={site} path={`/${path}`}>
  <section class="border-b border-cyan-300/20 bg-[radial-gradient(circle_at_20%_0%,#155e75,transparent_30%),linear-gradient(135deg,#020617,#0f172a_55%,#111827)] py-16">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="badge">{site.primaryKeyword} decision memo</span>
      <h1 class="hero-title mt-5">{title}</h1>
      <p class="mt-6 max-w-4xl text-xl text-slate-300">{desc} This page is written for operators building {site.angle}; it focuses on what to launch, what to measure, where the app can break, and how it should fit into a broader Shopify growth system.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  {parts[0] === 'apps' && !parts[1] && <section class="container py-14"><div class="mb-8"><span class="badge">App roster</span><h2 class="section-title mt-4">Ranked Shopify marketing app reviews</h2><p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-slate-300">This roster covers lifecycle email, SMS, popups, loyalty, reviews, referrals, analytics, search, upsells, and conversion tools. The ranking favors Shopify data depth, practical implementation, and whether the app helps a merchant operate more intelligently over time.</p></div><div class="grid gap-5 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3">{APPS.map((app,i)=><a class="card" href={`/apps/${app.slug}`}><div class="text-sm font-black text-cyan-200">#{i+1} · {app.category}</div><h2 class="mt-3 text-2xl font-black text-white">{app.name}</h2><p class="mt-3 text-sm text-slate-300">Best for {app.bestFor}.</p><p class="mt-4 text-sm font-black text-cyan-100">{app.pricing}</p></a>)}</div></section>}

  {parts[0] === 'apps' && parts[1] && (() => { const app = appBySlug(parts[1])!; return <section class="container grid gap-8 py-14 lg:grid-cols-[1fr_340px]"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>What {app.name} does in a Shopify marketing stack</h2><p>{app.shopifyFit} For searches around <strong>{site.primaryKeyword}</strong>, the central question is not whether {app.name} can send a campaign or install a widget. The real question is whether it can convert Shopify events into better commercial decisions: who should be contacted, what proof or offer should be shown, which product context matters, and when the next message becomes too much.</p><p>{operatingNotes}</p><h2>Where {app.name} fits best</h2><p>{app.name} is strongest for {app.bestFor}. In a practical stack, that means it should own a clear job rather than sit beside five overlapping tools. A store should define the primary revenue motion before implementation: capture more subscribers, recover carts, educate new buyers, stimulate repeat orders, collect proof, grow loyalty, or explain attribution. Without that job definition, even a strong app becomes another dashboard nobody opens.</p><h2>Strengths that matter</h2><ul>{app.strengths.map(s=><li>{s}</li>)}</ul><p>The strengths above should be tested with live Shopify data. Build a small pilot around one segment and one purchase moment. Look for whether the tool exposes the fields your team actually uses: order count, products purchased, product viewed, discount sensitivity, consent status, location, customer value, subscription status, and recent engagement. A pretty editor is useful, but the data model determines how precise the marketing can become.</p><h2>Limits and failure modes</h2><ul>{app.limits.map(l=><li>{l}</li>)}</ul><p>The common failure mode is buying software before choosing the operating cadence. Marketing apps need owners. Someone must review segments, approve offers, refresh creative, watch deliverability or placement, and compare attributed revenue against total store behavior. If that work is skipped, the app may still report wins, but the merchant will not know whether it created durable profit.</p><h2>Shopify buying advice</h2><p>Choose {app.name} if its workflow depth matches your next ninety days of retention and conversion work. Skip it if the team only needs a one-off newsletter sender, a temporary pop-up, or a dashboard that duplicates reporting already available elsewhere. For {site.keywordPlural}, the winning tool is the one your team will actually operate weekly, learn from monthly, and keep connected to the customer journey as the store changes.</p></article><aside class="card h-fit"><div class="text-sm font-black uppercase tracking-wide text-cyan-200">Snapshot</div><dl class="mt-4 space-y-4 text-sm text-slate-300"><div><dt class="font-black text-white">Category</dt><dd>{app.category}</dd></div><div><dt class="font-black text-white">Pricing</dt><dd>{app.pricing}</dd></div><div><dt class="font-black text-white">Best for</dt><dd>{app.bestFor}</dd></div></dl><a class="btn btn-primary mt-6 w-full" href="https://sequenzy.com">Compare with Sequenzy</a></aside></section> })()}

  {parts[0] === 'compare' && !parts[1] && <section class="container py-14"><div class="mb-8"><span class="badge">Battlecards</span><h2 class="section-title mt-4">Side-by-side app comparisons</h2><p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-slate-300">Use these comparison pages to pick by business model, operating workload, and Shopify data depth rather than brand familiarity.</p></div><div class="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3">{pairs.map(([a,b])=><a class="card" href={`/compare/${a.slug}-vs-${b.slug}`}><h2 class="text-xl font-black text-white">{a.name} vs {b.name}</h2><p class="mt-2 text-sm text-slate-300">Which is better for {site.primaryKeyword.toLowerCase()}?</p></a>)}</div></section>}

  {parts[0] === 'compare' && parts[1] && (() => { const [a,b] = parts[1].split('-vs-').map(appBySlug); return <section class="container py-14"><div class="card overflow-x-auto"><table class="data-table"><thead><tr><th>Criteria</th><th>{a?.name}</th><th>{b?.name}</th><th>Shopify takeaway</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Best fit</td><td>{a?.bestFor}</td><td>{b?.bestFor}</td><td>Pick based on operating model, not logo recognition.</td></tr><tr><td>Pricing</td><td>{a?.pricing}</td><td>{b?.pricing}</td><td>Model costs against list growth, message volume, and team time.</td></tr><tr><td>Primary strength</td><td>{a?.strengths[0]}</td><td>{b?.strengths[0]}</td><td>{site.primaryKeyword} should create revenue you can defend.</td></tr></tbody></table></div><article class="prose-shopify mt-8 card"><h2>Verdict for {site.primaryKeyword}</h2><p>{a?.name} is usually better when you need {a?.bestFor}. {b?.name} is stronger when the store cares more about {b?.bestFor}. The right answer depends on the highest-value bottleneck in the store: acquisition capture, checkout recovery, product education, social proof, repeat purchase, loyalty, or analytics.</p><p>{operatingNotes}</p><p>If both tools look close, run a migration-risk test before committing. Can your team rebuild the top five revenue flows, segment by product and order history, preserve consent, keep creative consistent, and read revenue by campaign without manual spreadsheet work? If the answer is no for one option, the cheaper headline price may become expensive after launch.</p><h2>Implementation sequence</h2><p>Start with the job closest to cash. For most Shopify stores that means welcome capture, abandoned cart, post-purchase education, replenishment, or winback. Launch one flow, measure customer quality, then add the next layer only after reporting is trusted. This disciplined sequence prevents the marketing stack from becoming a noisy collection of automations with no owner.</p></article></section> })()}

  {parts[0] === 'for' && !parts[1] && <section class="container py-14"><div class="mb-8"><span class="badge">Segment maps</span><h2 class="section-title mt-4">Marketing stacks by store type</h2></div><div class="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-3">{SEGMENTS.map(s=><a class="card" href={`/for/${s.slug}`}><h2 class="text-xl font-black text-white">{s.name}</h2><p class="mt-2 text-sm text-slate-300">Primary marketing problem: {s.pain}.</p></a>)}</div></section>}
  {parts[0] === 'for' && parts[1] && (() => { const seg=SEGMENTS.find(s=>s.slug===parts[1])!; return <section class="container py-14"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>How {seg.name} should choose {site.primaryKeyword}</h2><p>{seg.name} have to account for {seg.pain}. That changes the app shortlist: the best choice is not always the largest platform, but the one that maps store-specific signals into timely, useful messages. A marketing stack for this segment should make the next customer action obvious without relying on constant discounts.</p><p>{operatingNotes}</p><h2>Recommended shortlist</h2><ul>{primaryApps.slice(0,8).map(a=><li><a class="link" href={`/apps/${a.slug}`}>{a.name}</a> — {a.bestFor}</li>)}</ul><h2>Implementation notes for {seg.name}</h2><p>Start with one money flow, one trust-building flow, and one reactivation flow. The money flow addresses the nearest purchase event: welcome, cart recovery, replenishment, or repeat order. The trust flow answers the reason a customer hesitates: proof, education, sizing, ingredients, quality, timing, or service. The reactivation flow protects the customer file from going cold by using purchase timing and category interest instead of blasting every lapsed buyer with the same coupon.</p><p>For {site.keywordPlural}, more campaigns are not automatically better. Better timing and cleaner segmentation usually beat extra sends. This is especially true when {seg.pain} affects the buying cycle. A merchant should document what data the app needs, what content must be created, and what metric will prove the flow deserves to remain live.</p></article></section> })()}

  {parts[0] === 'use-cases' && !parts[1] && <section class="container py-14"><div class="mb-8"><span class="badge">Play library</span><h2 class="section-title mt-4">Use cases for the full marketing stack</h2></div><div class="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-3">{USE_CASES.map(u=><a class="card" href={`/use-cases/${u.slug}`}><h2 class="text-xl font-black text-white">{u.name}</h2><p class="mt-2 text-sm text-slate-300">Use {site.primaryKeyword.toLowerCase()} to {u.job}.</p></a>)}</div></section>}
  {parts[0] === 'use-cases' && parts[1] && (() => { const u=USE_CASES.find(x=>x.slug===parts[1])!; return <section class="container py-14"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Best approach for {u.name}</h2><p>The job of {u.name} is to {u.job}. For {site.primaryKeyword}, that means using Shopify events, product context, consent, and customer history to decide who gets the message and when. A strong play should feel like a continuation of the shopping experience, not a disconnected blast from a marketing calendar.</p><p>{operatingNotes}</p><h2>Apps to consider</h2><ul>{primaryApps.slice(0,8).map(a=><li><a class="link" href={`/apps/${a.slug}`}>{a.name}</a>: {a.shopifyFit}</li>)}</ul><h2>What to measure</h2><p>Measure recovered revenue, repeat purchase rate, margin after discounts, unsubscribe or opt-out pressure, customer support issues, and revenue by segment. Avoid judging {u.name} only by opens, clicks, or platform-attributed revenue. The better question is whether the play changes the customer journey in a way that the store can keep funding.</p><h2>Launch checklist</h2><p>Before launch, define the trigger, exclusion rules, offer logic, creative promise, suppression window, and owner. After launch, review examples of real customers entering and exiting the flow. This small manual audit often catches problems dashboards miss: expired products, awkward timing, discount overlap, or a message that makes sense to marketers but not to shoppers.</p></article></section> })()}

  {parts[0] === 'alternatives' && (() => { const app=appBySlug((parts[1]||'').replace('-alternative',''))!; const alts=APPS.filter(a=>a.slug!==app.slug).slice(0,8); return <section class="container py-14"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Why Shopify stores look for {app.name} alternatives</h2><p>{app.name} is a credible option, but it is not always the right fit for every store searching for {site.primaryKeyword}. Common reasons to compare alternatives include pricing, channel mix, migration workload, segmentation depth, reporting confidence, team preference, and how much Shopify-specific context the app exposes inside daily workflows.</p><p>{operatingNotes}</p><h2>Best alternatives</h2><ul>{alts.map(a=><li><a class="link" href={`/apps/${a.slug}`}>{a.name}</a> — {a.bestFor}</li>)}</ul><h2>Selection rule</h2><p>Do not switch tools just for a cleaner interface. Switch when the alternative makes an important Shopify workflow easier to launch, easier to measure, or cheaper to scale. The safest migration begins with a single flow or widget, proves that reporting matches store reality, and only then moves the rest of the lifecycle program.</p></article></section> })()}

  {parts[0] === 'guides' && <section class="container py-14"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Shopify marketing app selection framework</h2><p>Pick {site.primaryKeyword} by matching your business model to lifecycle jobs. New stores need capture, welcome, cart recovery, proof, and first purchase campaigns. Growing stores need segmentation, post-purchase education, replenishment, loyalty, winback, and deliverability discipline. Larger brands need governance, experimentation, attribution, creative operations, and channel coordination.</p><p>{operatingNotes}</p><p>A practical audit starts with the customer journey, not the app store. Write down the moments where money leaks: anonymous visitors leave, subscribers never buy, carts stall, new customers get anxious, repeat purchase timing is missed, VIP buyers receive generic offers, reviews are not reused, and reporting cannot explain incrementality. Then choose tools that close the most expensive leaks first.</p><h2>Internal linking map</h2><ul><li><a class="link" href="/apps">All apps</a></li><li><a class="link" href="/compare">Comparison battlecards</a></li><li><a class="link" href="/use-cases/abandoned-cart">Abandoned cart guide</a></li><li><a class="link" href="/for/fashion">Fashion store guide</a></li></ul></article></section>}
</BaseLayout>
